{"cursor":"30928","size":15,"audio":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/da/Chanakya.ogg"],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Chanakya image = CHANAKYA.jpg image_size = alt = caption = An artist's\n| impression of Chanakya birth_date = c. 370 BCE\n| birth_place = | death_date = c. 283 BCE\n| death_place = Pataliputra residence = Pataliputra other_names = Kauá¹­ilya,\n| Vishnugupta alma_mater = Takshashila occupation = Professor and royal advisor\n| of Chandragupta Maurya known_for = Foundation of the Maurya Empire\n| notable_works = Arthashastra, Chanakya Neeti\n|religion = Jain\n| influences = influenced = footnotes =\n}} 'Chanakya' (c. 370â283 BCE) was an Indian\nteacher, philosopher and royal advisor.\n\nOriginally a professor of economics and political science at the ancient\nTakshashila University, Chanakya managed the first Maurya emperor Chandragupta's\nrise to power at a young age. He is widely credited for having played an\nimportant role in the establishment of the Maurya Empire, which was the first\nempire in archaeologically recorded history to rule most of the Indian\nsubcontinent. Chanakya served as the chief advisor to both Chandragupta and his\nson Bindusara.\n\nChanakya is traditionally identified as 'Kautilya' or 'Vishnu Gupta', who\nauthored the ancient Indian political treatise called ArthaÅÄstra. As such, he is considered as the pioneer of the field of\neconomics and political science in India, and his work is thought of as an\nimportant precursor to Classical Economics. L. K. Jha, K. N. Jha (1998).\n\"Chanakya: the pioneer economist of the world\", International Journal of Social\nEconomics '25' (2â4), p. 267â282. Waldauer, C.,\nZahka, W.J. and Pal, S. 1996. [http://bss.sfsu.edu/mbar/ECON605/Arthashastra.pdf\nKauá¹­ilya's Arthashastra: A neglected precursor to classical economics]. Indian\nEconomic Review, Vol. XXXI, No. 1, pp. 101â108. Tisdell, C. 2003.\n[http://espace.library.uq.edu.au/view/UQ:84337 A Western perspective of\nKauá¹­ilya's Arthasastra: does it provide a basis for economic science?]Economic\nTheory, Applications and Issues Working Paper No. 18. Brisbane: School of\nEconomics, The University of Queensland. Sihag, B.S. 2007. Kauá¹­ilya on\ninstitutions, governance, knowledge, ethics and prosperity.Humanomics'' 23 (1):\n5â28. Chanakya is often called the \"Indian\nMachiavelli\", [http://www.jstor.org/stable/2142992 \"The Indian Machiavelli\"\nor Political Theory in India Two Thousand Years Ago] by Herbert H. Gowen.\nPolitical Science Quarterly Vol. 44, No. 2 (Jun. 1929), pp. 173â192. Published\nby: The Academy of Political Science. although his works predate\nMachiavelli's by about 1,800 years. Herbert H. Gowen (1929).\n[http://www.jstor.org/stable/2142992 and in a much more conventional world.or\nPolitical Theory in India Two Thousand Years Ago], Political Science Quarterly\n'44' (2), p. 173â192. His works were lost near the end of the Gupta\ndynasty and not rediscovered until 1915.\n","linknr":781,"url":"chanakya","recorded":1371065253,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Chanakya&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Chanakya&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:CHANAKYA.jpg","//upload.wik